reason.tex:
%text First, find out where the three lines \underline\text{cut the x- and the y-axis}. That will give you two points which when joined form the line.
%
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|} \hline \text{Line} & \text{When }y=0 & \text{When }x=0 \\ \hline 2x + y =4 & (2,0) & (0,4) \\ \hline 3x-2y=6 & (2,0) & (0,-3) \\ \hline x-3y+5 = 0 & (-5,0) & (0,\frac{5}{3}) \\ \hline \end{tabular}

%text You would have noticed from Step 1 that $2x+y=4$ and $x-3y+5=0$ cut the x-axis at the same point $A=(2,0)$.
But even if you didn't, then to find the coordinates of the vertices take pairs of lines and \underline\text{solve for $x$ and $y$}.
% \begin{align} A: y=4-2x &= \frac{3x}{2}-3\implies x = 2, y = 0 \\ B: y=4-2x &= \frac{x}{3}+\frac{5}{3} \implies x = 1, y = 2 \\ C: y = \frac{x}{3}+\frac{5}{3} &= \frac{3x}{2}-3 \implies x = 4,y=3 \end{align}
